registros.occurrenceRemarks: Colombian Red Howler Monkey (Alouatta seniculus) xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx COMPARE TO My favorite Howler Monkey (Alouatta palliata) observations: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?taxon_id=633090&user_id=aparrot1&verifiable=any Alpha Male: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/189133674 Mother with Infant: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/189139553 Mother with Juvenile: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/153518033 Mantled Howler Monkey (Alouatta palliata) is a long-tailed primate in the Spider, Howler, and Woolly Monkeys (Atelidae) family. When a troupe of Mantled Howler Monkeys move through the tree canopy, it sounds like a strong, howling wind. Conservation Status: Vulnerable (VU) (IUCN Red List) due to habitat loss. "Mantled Howler Monkeys inhabit lowland and montane rain forests, including primary and regenerated forest habitats. Mantled howler monkeys are large and stocky with black fur, and most individuals have long, yellow or brown fur saddles. Long guard hairs are present on their flanks, earning the common name "mantled" howler monkey. The face is naked, black and bearded, and the prehensile tail has a naked pad on the underside near its base. Males have a prominent white scrotum, weigh 6 to 7 kg, and usually have a longer beard than female individuals." https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Alouatta_palliata/ Mantled Howler Monkeys "are very agile swinging through tree branches with long arms, legs, and tail. The prehensile tail is 21-26 inches long. Mantled Howler Monkey is one of the New World monkey species most often seen and heard in the wild in Central America. It takes its "mantled" name from the long guard hairs on its sides. The mantled howler is one of the largest Central American monkeys, and males can weigh up to 9.8 kg (22 lb). It is the only Central American monkey that eats large quantities of leaves; it has several adaptations to this folivorous diet. Since leaves are difficult to digest and provide less energy than most foods, the mantled howler spends the majority of each day resting and sleeping. The male mantled howler has an enlarged hyoid bone, a hollow bone near the vocal cords, which amplifies the calls made by the male, and is the reason for the name "howler". Howling allows the monkeys to locate each other without expending energy on moving or risking physical confrontation. The mantled howler lives in groups that can have over 40 members, although groups are usually smaller. Most mantled howlers of both sexes are evicted from the group they were born in upon reaching sexual maturity, resulting in most adult group members being unrelated. The most dominant male, the alpha male, gets preference for food and resting places, and mates with most of the receptive females. The mantled howler is important to the rainforest ecology as a seed disperser and germinator. Although it is affected by deforestation, it is able to adapt better than other species, due to its ability to feed on a variety of vegetation." https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/43436-Alouatta-palliata xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx Irene's Spider, Howler, and Woolly Monkeys (Atelidae) family observations on INaturalist, worldwide: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?taxon_id=71377&user_id=aparrot1&verifiable=any Irene's Primates observations worldwide (includes monkeys, lemurs,tamarins, titis, and more): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?project_id=90144&ttl=900&v=1745184783000&place_id=any&verifiable=any&subview=grid&user_id=3188668 Primates of the World: an INatualist Project: https://www.inaturalist.org/projects/primates-of-the-world Animal Diversity Web: https://animaldiversity.org/ Irene's (aparrot1) Profile Page on INaturalist listing Nature Resources (includes online references with links) for Plants, Birds, Fungi, Lepidoptera, Arachnids, Reptiles, Amphibians, Marine Life, Plant Galls, and more: https://www.inaturalist.org/people/3188668
